DSA-002D

---

### ✍️ **Definition:**

> Data types in Java define the type of data a variable can hold, like integer, decimal, character, or Boolean.
> 

---

### ✍️ **Why Use Data Types?**

> To define what kind of value (number, decimal, text, etc.) we want to store in a variable.
> 

---

### ✍️ **Types of Data Types in Java:**

There are 2 main types:

1. Primitive Data Types
2. Non-Primitive Data Types (Reference)

---

### ✍️ **1. Primitive Data Types:**

| Data Type | Size | Use Example |
| --- | --- | --- |
| int | 4 bytes | whole numbers → 10, -5 |
| float | 4 bytes | decimal → 3.14f |
| double | 8 bytes | large decimal → 3.141592 |
| char | 2 bytes | single letter → 'A' |
| boolean | 1 bit | true or false |
| byte | 1 byte | small numbers → -128 to 127 |
| short | 2 bytes | short numbers |
| long | 8 bytes | bigger numbers → 123456L |

---

### ✍️ **2. Non-Primitive (Reference) Data Types:**

| Type | Use Example |
| --- | --- |
| String | Text → "Bablu" |
| Arrays | Collection of data |
| Classes | User-defined types |

---

### 💡 **Logic in 1 Line:**

**Data type = tells what kind of value a variable can store.**

---

### 💻 Code:

```java
java
CopyEdit
public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        int age = 20;
        float price = 99.99f;
        double pi = 3.141592;
        char grade = 'A';
        boolean isPass = true;
        String name = "Bablu";

        System.out.println("Age: " + age);
        System.out.println("Price: " + price);
        System.out.println("Pi: " + pi);
        System.out.println("Grade: " + grade);
        System.out.println("Passed: " + isPass);
        System.out.println("Name: " + name);
    }
}
```
